  "nursesNote": "When a patient is hallucinating (a false sensory experience, most often hearing voices), the nurse first asks what the voices are saying to assess for command hallucinations that tell the patient to harm self or others, which is a safety priority. The nurse acknowledges the patient's experience and the feelings behind it (the experience is real to them) without reinforcing the hallucination: the nurse does not pretend to see or hear it and does not argue about whether it is real, since both increase distress. Reality is presented calmly and simply, for example, 'I don't hear any voices, but I can see you feel frightened.' The nurse reduces environmental stimulation, speaks in short, calm sentences, and redirects the patient to reality-based activities or conversation. Escalating distress is monitored and the nurse stays with the patient as needed.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Ask what the voices are saying to assess for command hallucinations",
    "Acknowledge the patient's feelings without reinforcing the hallucination",
    "Do not pretend to see or hear it, and do not argue",
    "Calmly present reality in simple terms",
    "Reduce stimulation and redirect to reality-based activity"
  ],
